00:39:13.640 --> 00:39:14.520
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:39:14.520 --> 00:39:16.340
I separated K and K prime.

00:39:16.340 --> 00:39:16.870
Yes.

00:39:16.870 --> 00:39:18.529
K and U, yes.

00:39:18.529 --> 00:39:19.070
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:39:19.070 --> 00:39:22.430
So if you want to do a
renormalization group again,

00:39:22.430 --> 00:39:23.390
we'll need to--

00:39:23.390 --> 00:39:24.100
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:39:24.100 --> 00:39:24.847
Do this.

00:39:24.847 --> 00:39:26.040
AUDIENCE: Again [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:26.040 --> 00:39:26.831
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:39:26.831 --> 00:39:27.650
Yeah.

00:39:27.650 --> 00:39:30.560
But we do it once, and we
have the recursion relation.

00:39:30.560 --> 00:39:32.210
And then we stop.

00:39:32.210 --> 00:39:33.160
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:39:33.160 --> 00:39:34.700
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:39:34.700 --> 00:39:35.200
Yes?

00:39:35.200 --> 00:39:40.300
AUDIENCE: Is this possible
for other odd number lattices?

00:39:40.300 --> 00:39:42.680
Will you still
preserve the parameter?

00:39:42.680 --> 00:39:43.570
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:39:43.570 --> 00:39:46.140
It's even possible
for square lattices

00:39:46.140 --> 00:39:47.559
with some modification,
and that's

00:39:47.559 --> 00:39:49.225
what you'll have in
one of the problems.

00:39:55.141 --> 00:39:55.640
OK?

00:40:00.980 --> 00:40:01.840
Fine.

00:40:01.840 --> 00:40:03.100
But the point is-- OK.

00:40:03.100 --> 00:40:04.210
So I stopped here.

00:40:04.210 --> 00:40:10.760
So K star was 0.27, which is
the coupling that separates

00:40:10.760 --> 00:40:13.420
places where you go
to uncorrelated spins,

00:40:13.420 --> 00:40:17.010
places you go to everything
ordered together.

00:40:17.010 --> 00:40:20.200
It turns out that the
triangular lattice is something

00:40:20.200 --> 00:40:21.850
that one can solve exactly.

00:40:21.850 --> 00:40:23.400
It's one of the few things.

00:40:23.400 --> 00:40:25.570
And you'll have the pleasure
of serving that also

00:40:25.570 --> 00:40:27.260
in a problem set.

00:40:27.260 --> 00:40:32.620
And you will show that KC, the
correct value of the coupling,

00:40:32.620 --> 00:40:36.630
is something like 0.33.

00:40:36.630 --> 00:40:41.865
So that gives you an idea of how
good or bad this approximation

00:40:41.865 --> 00:40:43.510
is.

00:40:43.510 --> 00:40:46.260
But the point in any
case is that the location

00:40:46.260 --> 00:40:48.050
of the coupling is
not that important.

00:40:48.050 --> 00:40:51.304
We have discussed that
it is non-universal.

00:40:51.304 --> 00:40:53.345
The thing that maybe we
should be more interested

00:40:53.345 --> 00:40:59.320
in is what happens if I'm
in the vicinity of this,

00:40:59.320 --> 00:41:01.920
how rapidly do I move away?

00:41:01.920 --> 00:41:04.910
And actually I have to show
that we are moving away.

00:41:04.910 --> 00:41:07.610
But because of topology,
it's more or less obvious

00:41:07.610 --> 00:41:09.590
that it should be that way.

00:41:09.590 --> 00:41:13.220
So what I need to do is
evaluate this at K star.

00:41:13.220 --> 00:41:14.340
OK.

00:41:14.340 --> 00:41:18.100
Now you can see that K
prime is a function of K.

00:41:18.100 --> 00:41:20.680
So what you need to do
is to take derivatives.

00:41:20.680 --> 00:41:24.560
So thers' some
algebra involved here.

00:41:24.560 --> 00:41:27.810
And then, once you have
taken the derivative,

00:41:27.810 --> 00:41:30.920
you have to put the
value of K star.

00:41:30.920 --> 00:41:33.840
And here, some
calculator is necessary.

00:41:33.840 --> 00:41:36.870
And at the end of the day, the
number that you get, I believe,

00:41:36.870 --> 00:41:39.460
is something like 1.62.

00:41:39.460 --> 00:41:41.280
Yes.

00:41:41.280 --> 00:41:44.180
And so that says
since being it's

00:41:44.180 --> 00:41:48.240
larger than 1, that you
will be pushed away.

00:41:48.240 --> 00:41:52.040
But these things have
been important to us

00:41:52.040 --> 00:41:56.566
as indicators of
these exponents.

00:41:56.566 --> 00:41:59.640
In particular, I'm on the
subspace that has symmetry,

00:41:59.640 --> 00:42:03.470
so I should be
calculating yt here.

00:42:03.470 --> 00:42:07.260
As was pointed out,
important to this step

00:42:07.260 --> 00:42:10.440
is knowing what the value
of B is, which we can either

00:42:10.440 --> 00:42:12.910
look at by the ratio of
the lattice constants

00:42:12.910 --> 00:42:16.630
or by the fact that I have
removed one third of the spins.

00:42:16.630 --> 00:42:19.970
It has to be root
3 to the power yt.

00:42:19.970 --> 00:42:27.005
So my yt is log of 1.62
divided by log of root 3.

00:42:27.005 --> 00:42:29.890
So again you go and
look at your calculator,

00:42:29.890 --> 00:42:37.360
and the answer comes
out to be 0.88.

00:42:37.360 --> 00:42:42.300
Now the exact value of yt for
all two-dimensionalizing models

00:42:42.300 --> 00:42:43.940
is 1.

00:42:43.940 --> 00:42:48.070
So again, this is an
indicator of how good or bad

00:42:48.070 --> 00:42:51.791
you have done at this
ordering perturbation tier.

00:42:51.791 --> 00:42:53.540
OK.

00:42:53.540 --> 00:42:57.880
Now, answering the question
that you had before,

00:42:57.880 --> 00:43:01.380
suppose I were to go
to order of U squared?

00:43:04.105 --> 00:43:08.260
Now, order of U
squared, I have to take

00:43:08.260 --> 00:43:12.080
this kind of interaction,
which is bilinear.

00:43:12.080 --> 00:43:16.080
Let's say pair of spins
here, multiply two of them,

00:43:16.080 --> 00:43:19.900
so I will get a pair of spins
here and pair of spins there.

00:43:19.900 --> 00:43:23.150
As long as they are
distinct locations when

00:43:23.150 --> 00:43:28.440
I subtract the average squared,
they will subtract out.

00:43:28.440 --> 00:43:31.650
So the only place where I
will get something non-trivial

00:43:31.650 --> 00:43:35.190
is if I pick one
here and one here.

00:43:35.190 --> 00:43:38.240
And by that kind
of reasoning, you

00:43:38.240 --> 00:43:42.920
can convince yourself that
what happens at next order

00:43:42.920 --> 00:43:46.590
is that in addition to
interactions between neighbors,

00:43:46.590 --> 00:43:50.550
you will degenerate interactions
between things that are two

00:43:50.550 --> 00:43:56.390
apart and things that
are, well, three apart,

00:43:56.390 --> 00:43:58.890
so basically next
nearest neighbors

00:43:58.890 --> 00:44:01.380
and next next nearest neighbors.

00:44:01.380 --> 00:44:03.590
So what you will
have, even if you

00:44:03.590 --> 00:44:07.770
start with a form
such as this, you

00:44:07.770 --> 00:44:16.649
will generate next nearest
neighbor and next next nearest

00:44:16.649 --> 00:44:17.565
neighbor interactions.

00:44:21.610 --> 00:44:25.250
Let's call them K, L, M.

00:44:25.250 --> 00:44:30.490
So to be consistent, you have
to go back to the original model

00:44:30.490 --> 00:44:35.270
and put the three interactions
and construct recursion

00:44:35.270 --> 00:44:37.260
relations from the
three parameters,

00:44:37.260 --> 00:44:41.090
K, L, M, to the new
three parameters.

00:44:41.090 --> 00:44:43.170
More or less following
this procedure,

00:44:43.170 --> 00:44:45.580
it's several pages of algebra.

00:44:45.580 --> 00:44:47.370
So I won't do it.

00:44:47.370 --> 00:44:49.500
Niemeijer and van
Leeuwen did it,

00:44:49.500 --> 00:44:53.340
and they calculated
the yt at next order

00:44:53.340 --> 00:44:56.530
by finding the fixed point in
this three-dimensional space.

00:44:56.530 --> 00:45:00.510
It has one relevant direction,
and that one relevant direction

00:45:00.510 --> 00:45:06.840
gave them an eigenvalue that
was extremely close to 1.

00:45:06.840 --> 00:45:12.980
So I don't believe anybody
has taken this to next order.

00:45:12.980 --> 00:45:17.290
You've got good enough,
might as well stop.

00:45:17.290 --> 00:45:20.440
I think it's not going
to improve and get better

00:45:20.440 --> 00:45:23.560
because this is an
uncontrolled approximation.

00:45:23.560 --> 00:45:25.895
So it's likely to be
one of those cases,

00:45:25.895 --> 00:45:28.385
that you asymptotically
approach the good result

00:45:28.385 --> 00:45:29.830
and then move away.

00:45:33.520 --> 00:45:37.030
Now once I have
yt, I can naturally

00:45:37.030 --> 00:45:40.520
calculate exponents
such as alpha.

00:45:40.520 --> 00:45:44.760
First of all U,
which is 1 over yt.

00:45:44.760 --> 00:45:49.210
1 over 0.88 is
something like 1.13.

00:45:49.210 --> 00:45:53.330
And the exact result would be
the inverse of 1 which is 1.

00:45:53.330 --> 00:46:00.746
And I can calculate alpha, which
is 2 minus d, which is 2 mu.

00:46:00.746 --> 00:46:07.150
With that value of U,
I will get minus 0.26.

00:46:07.150 --> 00:46:09.630
Again, the correct result
would be corresponding

00:46:09.630 --> 00:46:11.910
to a logarithmic divergence.

00:46:11.910 --> 00:46:16.290
So this zeroed order, OK.

00:46:16.290 --> 00:46:23.560
Those things, let's say, for
the exponents to 10%, 20%.

00:46:23.560 --> 00:46:26.430
You would say that, OK,
what about other exponents,

00:46:26.430 --> 00:46:30.100
such as beta,
gamma, and so forth.

00:46:30.100 --> 00:46:36.305
Clearly, to get those exponents,
I also need to have yh.

00:46:36.305 --> 00:46:38.250
OK.

00:46:38.250 --> 00:46:54.460
So to get yh, I will add, as
an additional perturbation,

00:46:54.460 --> 00:47:00.120
a term which is h sum
over i sigma i, which

00:47:00.120 --> 00:47:04.730
is, of course, the same thing
as sum over alpha, sigma alpha

00:47:04.730 --> 00:47:10.640
of 1 plus sigma alpha
2 plus sigma alpha 3.

00:47:15.440 --> 00:47:17.740
And if I regard this
as a perturbation,

00:47:17.740 --> 00:47:21.080
you can see that in the
perturbative scheme,

00:47:21.080 --> 00:47:25.200
this would go under
the transformation

00:47:25.200 --> 00:47:31.720
to the average of this
quantity, and that the average

00:47:31.720 --> 00:47:35.890
of this quantity will
give me 3 for each cell.

00:47:35.890 --> 00:47:39.370
So I will get 3h.

00:47:39.370 --> 00:47:41.900
And for each cell, I
will get the average

00:47:41.900 --> 00:47:44.810
of a site spin, which is
related to the cell spin

00:47:44.810 --> 00:47:46.940
through this factor
that we calculated,

00:47:46.940 --> 00:47:53.250
e to the 3K e to the minus k e
to the 3k plus 3e to the minus

00:47:53.250 --> 00:47:56.440
k sigma alpha prime.

00:47:56.440 --> 00:48:00.490
So we can see that by
generating h prime,

00:48:00.490 --> 00:48:04.710
which is 3h times
e to the 3K plus

00:48:04.710 --> 00:48:13.450
e to the minus K e to the
3K plus 3e to the minus K.

00:48:13.450 --> 00:48:19.800
And I can evaluate d
to the yh as dh prime

00:48:19.800 --> 00:48:24.090
by dh evaluated at
the fixed point.

00:48:24.090 --> 00:48:30.000
So I will get essentially
3 times this factor

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:32.730
evaluated at the fixed point.

00:48:32.730 --> 00:48:35.070
But we can see that
at the fixed point,

00:48:35.070 --> 00:48:38.070
this factor is 1 over root 2.

00:48:38.070 --> 00:48:41.160
So the answer is 3 over root 2.

00:48:41.160 --> 00:48:48.170
And my yh would be the log of 3
over root 2 divided by log of b

00:48:48.170 --> 00:48:52.670
that we said is
square root of 3.

00:48:52.670 --> 00:48:56.440
Put it in the calculator,
you get a number

00:48:56.440 --> 00:48:59.670
that is of the order of 1.4.

00:48:59.670 --> 00:49:07.310
And exact yh is 1.875.

00:49:07.310 --> 00:49:10.990
So again, once you have yh,
you can go and calculate

00:49:10.990 --> 00:49:13.350
through the exponent
scaling relations all

00:49:13.350 --> 00:49:15.968
the other exponents
that you have like beta.

00:49:19.420 --> 00:49:23.220
So not bad,
considering that if you

00:49:23.220 --> 00:49:26.250
wanted to go through epsilon
expansion, how much difficulty

00:49:26.250 --> 00:49:27.650
you would have.

00:49:27.650 --> 00:49:30.550
And in any case, we
are at two dimensions,

00:49:30.550 --> 00:49:33.190
which is far away from four.

00:49:33.190 --> 00:49:35.990
And getting results
at 2 is worse than

00:49:35.990 --> 00:49:38.070
trying to get results
at three dimensions.

00:49:47.990 --> 00:49:51.620
Now we want to do the procedure
as an approximation that

00:49:51.620 --> 00:49:54.240
is even simpler than this.

00:49:54.240 --> 00:49:58.420
And for that-- so that was
the Niemeijer-van Leeuwen

00:49:58.420 --> 00:49:59.790
procedure.

00:49:59.790 --> 00:50:03.140
The next one is due to
Kadanoff again and Migdal.

00:50:10.230 --> 00:50:11.650
And it's called bond-moving.

00:50:16.360 --> 00:50:19.550
And again, we have to
do an approximation.

00:50:19.550 --> 00:50:23.326
You can't do things exact.

00:50:23.326 --> 00:50:28.800
So let's demonstrate that
by a square lattice, which

00:50:28.800 --> 00:50:31.987
is much easier to draw than
the triangular lattice.

00:50:45.930 --> 00:50:50.650
And let's kind of
follow the procedure

00:50:50.650 --> 00:50:54.520
that we had for the
one-dimensional case.

00:50:54.520 --> 00:51:00.230
Let's say we want to do
rescaling by a factor of 2.

00:51:00.230 --> 00:51:04.360
And I want to keep this
spin, this spin, this spin,

00:51:04.360 --> 00:51:12.550
this spin, this spin and get
rid of all of the other spins

00:51:12.550 --> 00:51:13.910
that I have.

00:51:13.910 --> 00:51:16.930
Not the circular
round, much as I

00:51:16.930 --> 00:51:20.740
did for the
one-dimensional case.

00:51:20.740 --> 00:51:25.390
And the problem is
that if I'm summing

00:51:25.390 --> 00:51:28.800
over this spin over
here, there are

00:51:28.800 --> 00:51:34.890
paths that connect that
spin to other spins.

00:51:34.890 --> 00:51:38.430
So by necessity, once I sum
over all of these spins,

00:51:38.430 --> 00:51:41.416
I will generate all
kinds of interactions.

00:51:44.410 --> 00:51:49.860
So the problem is all of these
paths that connect things.

00:51:49.860 --> 00:51:53.410
So maybe-- and this is
called bond-moving--

00:51:53.410 --> 00:51:58.160
maybe I can remove all of these
things that are going to cause

00:51:58.160 --> 00:51:59.081
problem for--

00:52:04.490 --> 00:52:07.160
So if I do that, then
the only connection

00:52:07.160 --> 00:52:11.080
between this spin and this
spin comes from that side,

00:52:11.080 --> 00:52:14.480
between this spin and that
spin comes from that side.

00:52:14.480 --> 00:52:19.070
And if the original interaction
was K and I sum over this,

00:52:19.070 --> 00:52:25.580
I will get K prime, which is
what I have over there, 1/2 log

00:52:25.580 --> 00:52:30.230
cos 2K, because the
only thing that I did

00:52:30.230 --> 00:52:34.300
was to connect this
site to two neighbors,

00:52:34.300 --> 00:52:36.220
and then effectively,
it's the same thing

00:52:36.220 --> 00:52:39.010
as I was doing
for one dimension.

00:52:39.010 --> 00:52:41.960
So clearly this is a
very bad approximation,

00:52:41.960 --> 00:52:44.340
because I have reproduced
the same result

00:52:44.340 --> 00:52:47.410
as one dimension for the
two-dimensional case.

00:52:47.410 --> 00:52:50.380
And the reason is that
I weakened the lattice

00:52:50.380 --> 00:52:53.690
so drastically, I removed
most of the bonds.

00:52:53.690 --> 00:53:00.830
So there isn't that much weight
for the lattice to order.

00:53:00.830 --> 00:53:04.940
Kadanoff and Migdal
suggested was, OK.

00:53:04.940 --> 00:53:07.770
Let's not to remove these bonds.

00:53:07.770 --> 00:53:12.070
Just move them to some place
that they don't cause any harm.

00:53:12.070 --> 00:53:15.510
So I take this bond and
I strengthen this bond.

00:53:15.510 --> 00:53:18.290
I take this bond,
strengthen this one.

00:53:18.290 --> 00:53:19.890
This one goes to this one.

00:53:19.890 --> 00:53:22.320
Essentially what
happens is you can

00:53:22.320 --> 00:53:28.810
see that each one of the bonds
has been strengthened by 2.

00:53:28.810 --> 00:53:31.410
So I have this because
of the strength.

00:53:35.340 --> 00:53:40.200
So as simple as you can get to
construct a potential recursion

00:53:40.200 --> 00:53:43.070
relation for this
square lattice.

00:53:43.070 --> 00:53:46.890
So this is a way
that the parameter K

00:53:46.890 --> 00:53:51.520
changes, going
from 0 to infinity.

00:53:51.520 --> 00:53:54.260
And we can do the same thing
that we did over there.

00:53:54.260 --> 00:54:02.740
So we can check that for K going
zero, if I look at K prime,

00:54:02.740 --> 00:54:08.660
it is approximately 1/2 log of
hyperbolic cosine of something

00:54:08.660 --> 00:54:10.720
that is close to 0.

00:54:10.720 --> 00:54:15.230
So that becomes 1 plus the
square of this quantity, which

00:54:15.230 --> 00:54:19.110
is 4K squared over 2.

00:54:19.110 --> 00:54:26.856
And taking the log of that,
it becomes 4K squared.

00:54:26.856 --> 00:54:30.170
The factor of 4 does
not really matter.

00:54:30.170 --> 00:54:33.490
If K is very small,
like 1 over 100,

00:54:33.490 --> 00:54:35.820
K squared would be
10 to the minus 4.

00:54:35.820 --> 00:54:41.750
So basically, you certainly
have the expected behavior

00:54:41.750 --> 00:54:46.340
of becoming disordered if you
have a [INAUDIBLE] interaction.

00:54:46.340 --> 00:54:48.790
If you have a strong
enough coupling,

00:54:48.790 --> 00:54:50.860
however, are we
different from what

00:54:50.860 --> 00:54:53.110
we did for the
one-dimensional case?

00:54:53.110 --> 00:54:55.560
Well, the answer is
that in this case,

00:54:55.560 --> 00:55:04.260
K prime is 1/2 log
hyperbolic cosine of 4K,

00:55:04.260 --> 00:55:09.320
starts as e to the 4K plus e
to the minus 4K divided by 2.

00:55:09.320 --> 00:55:12.360
e to the minus 4K I can ignore.

00:55:12.360 --> 00:55:16.680
So you can see that in
this case, I will have 2K.

00:55:16.680 --> 00:55:20.440
I can even ignore the minus
log 2, which previously

00:55:20.440 --> 00:55:23.950
was so important because
previously we had 1 here

00:55:23.950 --> 00:55:27.710
and now it became 2, which means
that if I start to be 10,000,

00:55:27.710 --> 00:55:32.010
it will become 20,000,
40,000 and now you're

00:55:32.010 --> 00:55:34.220
going this direction.

00:55:34.220 --> 00:55:37.350
So again, by necessity
almost, I must

00:55:37.350 --> 00:55:42.590
have a fixed point at
some value in between.

00:55:42.590 --> 00:55:48.290
So I essentially have
to solve for K star

00:55:48.290 --> 00:55:57.510
as K star is 1/2
log cos of 4K star.

00:55:57.510 --> 00:56:01.710
You can recast this as some
algebraic equation in terms

00:56:01.710 --> 00:56:06.920
of e to the 4k e to the
K star and manipulate it.

00:56:06.920 --> 00:56:09.920
And after you do
your algebra, you

00:56:09.920 --> 00:56:14.530
will eventually come up
with a value of K star,

00:56:14.530 --> 00:56:24.280
which I believe is 0.3.

00:56:24.280 --> 00:56:29.370
You can ask, well, the square
lattice we will solve in class.

00:56:29.370 --> 00:56:33.000
I said the triangular lattice
I will leave for you to solve.

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:38.140
KC for the square lattice
is something like 0.44.

00:56:38.140 --> 00:56:44.150
So you are off by about 25%.

00:56:44.150 --> 00:56:46.890
Of course, again, the quantity
that you're interested in

00:56:46.890 --> 00:56:49.550
is b to t yt.

00:56:49.550 --> 00:56:51.550
b is 2 in this case.

00:56:51.550 --> 00:56:54.370
The length scale has
changed by a factor of 2,

00:56:54.370 --> 00:57:00.530
which is dk prime by
dk evaluated as K star,

00:57:00.530 --> 00:57:04.140
again, a combination of doing
the algebra of derivatives,

00:57:04.140 --> 00:57:09.270
evaluating at K star, and
then ultimately taking the log

00:57:09.270 --> 00:57:11.660
to convert it to a yt.

00:57:11.660 --> 00:57:16.460
And you come up with a value
of yt that is around 0.75.

00:57:16.460 --> 00:57:20.360
And, as I said, the exact
yt, which doesn't depend on

00:57:20.360 --> 00:57:22.320
whether you are dealing
with a square lattice

00:57:22.320 --> 00:57:24.510
or a triangular
lattice-- it's only

00:57:24.510 --> 00:57:28.100
a function of symmetry
and dimensionality-- is 1.

00:57:32.710 --> 00:57:38.570
So you can see that gradually we
are simplifying the complexity.

00:57:38.570 --> 00:57:42.110
Now we could, within
this approximation,

00:57:42.110 --> 00:57:45.980
solve everything
within one panel.

00:57:45.980 --> 00:57:48.410
Now this kind of
approximation, again,

00:57:48.410 --> 00:57:50.800
is not particularly very good.

00:57:50.800 --> 00:57:55.760
But it's a quick and dirty
way of getting results.

00:57:55.760 --> 00:57:59.900
And the advantage of it
is that you can do this

00:57:59.900 --> 00:58:04.459
not only in two dimensions, but
in higher dimensions as well.

00:58:21.450 --> 00:58:28.340
So let's say that you
had a cubic lattice

00:58:28.340 --> 00:58:32.520
and you were doing rescaling
by a factor of 2, which

00:58:32.520 --> 00:58:38.580
means that originally
you had spins along

00:58:38.580 --> 00:58:42.440
the various diagonals
and so forth--

00:58:42.440 --> 00:58:50.300
around the various partitions
of a square of size 2 x 2,

00:58:50.300 --> 00:58:55.490
and you want to keep
interactions among these

00:58:55.490 --> 00:59:00.120
and get rid of the interactions
among all of the places

00:59:00.120 --> 00:59:01.430
that you are not interested in.

00:59:04.070 --> 00:59:08.370
And the way that you do
that is precisely as before.

00:59:08.370 --> 00:59:12.071
You move these interactions
and strengthen the things

00:59:12.071 --> 00:59:13.070
that you have over here.

00:59:16.190 --> 00:59:18.510
Now whereas the number
of bonds that you

00:59:18.510 --> 00:59:23.390
had to move for the
square lattice was 2--

00:59:23.390 --> 00:59:26.860
the enhancement factor
was 2-- turns out

00:59:26.860 --> 00:59:31.880
that the enhancement factor in
three dimensions would be 4.

00:59:31.880 --> 00:59:35.690
You essentially have to take
one from here, one from there,

00:59:35.690 --> 00:59:36.970
one from there.

00:59:36.970 --> 00:59:40.460
So 1 plus 3 becomes 4.

00:59:40.460 --> 00:59:42.500
And you can convince
yourself that if I

00:59:42.500 --> 00:59:55.790
had done this in d-dimensional
hypercubic lattice, what

00:59:55.790 --> 01:00:00.860
I would have gotten is again
the one-dimensional recursion

01:00:00.860 --> 01:00:11.770
relation, except for this
enhancement factor, which

01:00:11.770 --> 01:00:19.490
is 2 to the power of d
minus 1 in d dimensions.

01:00:19.490 --> 01:00:25.250
Actually, I could even do
that for rescaling rather

01:00:25.250 --> 01:00:30.380
by a factor 2, by a factor of b.

01:00:30.380 --> 01:00:33.850
And hopefully, you
can convince yourself

01:00:33.850 --> 01:00:38.621
that it will become b to
the d minus 1 times 2K.

01:00:41.390 --> 01:00:46.620
And essentially that
factor is a cross section

01:00:46.620 --> 01:00:48.910
that you have to remove.

01:00:48.910 --> 01:00:56.020
So the cross-sectional area that
you encounter grows as the size

01:00:56.020 --> 01:00:58.560
to the power of d minus 1.

01:00:58.560 --> 01:01:02.540
And a kind of obvious
consequence of that

01:01:02.540 --> 01:01:06.470
is that if I go to the limit
of K going to infinity,

01:01:06.470 --> 01:01:13.020
you can see that K prime b would
go like b to the d minus 1K.

01:01:13.020 --> 01:01:18.200
Essentially, if you were to
have some kind of a system

01:01:18.200 --> 01:01:21.620
and you make pluses on one
side, minuses on the one side,

01:01:21.620 --> 01:01:24.880
to break it, then,
the number of bonds

01:01:24.880 --> 01:01:26.880
that you would
have to break would

01:01:26.880 --> 01:01:29.430
grow like the
cross-sectional area.

01:01:29.430 --> 01:01:33.630
So that's where that comes from.

01:01:33.630 --> 01:01:39.380
It turns out that, again,
this approach is exact

01:01:39.380 --> 01:01:42.710
as we've seen for one dimension.

01:01:42.710 --> 01:01:48.860
As we go to higher dimensions,
it becomes worse and worse.

01:01:48.860 --> 01:01:52.170
So I showed you how bad
it was in two dimensions.

01:01:52.170 --> 01:01:55.130
If I calculate the fixed point
and the exponents in three

01:01:55.130 --> 01:01:59.920
dimensions compared to our best
numerical result, it is off by,

01:01:59.920 --> 01:02:04.560
I don't know, 40%, 50%,
whereas 25% over there.

01:02:04.560 --> 01:02:07.350
So it gradually gets
worse and worse.

01:02:07.350 --> 01:02:10.985
And so one approach that
people have tried to do,

01:02:10.985 --> 01:02:13.700
which, again, doesn't
seem to be very rigorous

01:02:13.700 --> 01:02:18.085
is to convert this into an
expansion on dimensionality

01:02:18.085 --> 01:02:20.210
of 1.

01:02:20.210 --> 01:02:22.980
So it's roughly
correct that it's

01:02:22.980 --> 01:02:27.630
going to be close to 1--
correct close to one dimension.

01:02:27.630 --> 01:02:30.400
But as opposed to the
previous epsilon expansion,

01:02:30.400 --> 01:02:33.690
there doesn't seem to be a
controlled way to do this.

01:02:39.670 --> 01:02:43.850
I showed you how to do
this for Ising models.

01:02:43.850 --> 01:02:53.360
Actually, you can do
this for any spin model.

01:02:59.910 --> 01:03:04.530
So let's imagine that we have
some kind of a model that's

01:03:04.530 --> 01:03:07.290
in one dimension.

01:03:07.290 --> 01:03:11.515
At each site, we
have some variable

01:03:11.515 --> 01:03:15.130
that as i that I will
not specify what it is,

01:03:15.130 --> 01:03:18.480
how many variables-- how
many values it takes.

01:03:18.480 --> 01:03:23.370
But it interacts only with
its neighboring sites.

01:03:23.370 --> 01:03:29.940
And so presumably, there
is some interaction

01:03:29.940 --> 01:03:32.770
that depends on the two sites.

01:03:32.770 --> 01:03:36.480
There may be multiple
couplings implicit in this

01:03:36.480 --> 01:03:42.170
if I try to write this in terms
of the dot product of spins

01:03:42.170 --> 01:03:45.690
or things like this.

01:03:45.690 --> 01:03:51.070
So if I were to calculate
the partition function in one

01:03:51.070 --> 01:03:55.320
dimension-- I already
mentioned this last time--

01:03:55.320 --> 01:04:00.320
I have to do a sum
over what this spin is

01:04:00.320 --> 01:04:10.310
of e to the K of si si
plus 1 and a product

01:04:10.310 --> 01:04:13.810
over subsequent sites.

01:04:13.810 --> 01:04:20.910
And if I regard this as a
matrix, which is generally

01:04:20.910 --> 01:04:24.430
called a transfer
matrix, you can

01:04:24.430 --> 01:04:28.360
see that this
multiplication involving

01:04:28.360 --> 01:04:32.270
the sum over all of the
spins is equivalent to matrix

01:04:32.270 --> 01:04:34.020
multiplication.

01:04:34.020 --> 01:04:38.640
And, in particular, if I have
periodic boundary conditions

01:04:38.640 --> 01:04:42.890
in which the last spin
couples to the first spin,

01:04:42.890 --> 01:04:49.070
I would have trace of
T to the power of N,

01:04:49.070 --> 01:04:56.434
where t is essentially this,
e to the K of si si plus 1.

01:05:00.900 --> 01:05:09.570
Now, clearly I can
write this as trace of T

01:05:09.570 --> 01:05:14.070
squared to the
power of N over 2.

01:05:14.070 --> 01:05:15.960
Right.

01:05:15.960 --> 01:05:21.010
And this I can regard as
the partition function

01:05:21.010 --> 01:05:25.990
of a system that has
half as many spins.

01:05:25.990 --> 01:05:28.660
So I have performed the
renormalization group

01:05:28.660 --> 01:05:31.310
like what we are doing
in one dimension.

01:05:31.310 --> 01:05:34.550
I have T prime is T squared.

01:05:34.550 --> 01:05:37.880
And in general, you can see
that I can write this as N

01:05:37.880 --> 01:05:41.540
to the b N over b.

01:05:41.540 --> 01:05:45.610
So the result of
renormalization by a factor of b

01:05:45.610 --> 01:05:49.860
is simply one dimension to
take the matrix that you have

01:05:49.860 --> 01:05:53.690
and raise it to b power.

01:05:53.690 --> 01:05:54.396
OK.

01:05:54.396 --> 01:06:06.060
And so I could parameterize my
T by a set of interactions K,

01:06:06.060 --> 01:06:08.570
like we do for the Ising model.

01:06:08.570 --> 01:06:14.340
Raise it to the power of b,
and I would generate the matrix

01:06:14.340 --> 01:06:17.860
that I could then
parametrize by K prime,

01:06:17.860 --> 01:06:20.540
and I would have the
relationship between K prime

01:06:20.540 --> 01:06:25.160
and K in one dimension.

01:06:25.160 --> 01:06:29.560
So this is d equals 1.

01:06:29.560 --> 01:06:40.875
And the way to generalize
this Migdal Kadanoff, RG,

01:06:40.875 --> 01:06:45.510
to a very general
system is simply

01:06:45.510 --> 01:06:47.700
to enhance the couplings.

01:06:47.700 --> 01:06:50.570
So basically, what
I would write down

01:06:50.570 --> 01:06:56.140
is T prime, which, after
rescaling by a factor of b,

01:06:56.140 --> 01:07:01.000
is a function of a set of
parameters that I will K prime,

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:05.540
is obtained by taking the
matrix that I have for one set

01:07:05.540 --> 01:07:11.800
of couplings and raise
it to the power of b.

01:07:11.800 --> 01:07:14.950
This is the exact
one-dimensional result.

01:07:14.950 --> 01:07:19.125
And if I want to construct this
approximation in d dimensions,

01:07:19.125 --> 01:07:20.520
I will just do this.

01:07:24.890 --> 01:07:32.620
So for a while, before people
had sufficiently powerful

01:07:32.620 --> 01:07:37.160
computers to maybe
simulate things as easily,

01:07:37.160 --> 01:07:42.290
this was a good way to estimate
locations and exponents

01:07:42.290 --> 01:07:46.370
of phase diagrams,
critical exponents,

01:07:46.370 --> 01:07:49.850
et cetera for essentially
complicated problems

01:07:49.850 --> 01:07:53.760
that could have a set
of parameters even here.

01:07:53.760 --> 01:07:56.350
Nowadays, as I
said, you probably

01:07:56.350 --> 01:07:59.734
can do things much more easily
by computer simulations.

01:08:12.900 --> 01:08:17.569
So I guess I still have
another 10 minutes.

01:08:17.569 --> 01:08:21.949
I probably don't want
to start on the topic

01:08:21.949 --> 01:08:24.310
of the next lecture.

01:08:24.310 --> 01:08:27.439
But maybe what I'll do is
I'll expand a little bit

01:08:27.439 --> 01:08:32.370
on something that I mentioned
very rapidly last lecture,

01:08:32.370 --> 01:08:40.600
which is that in this
one-dimensional model where

01:08:40.600 --> 01:08:54.520
I solve the problem by
transfer matrix, what I have is

01:08:54.520 --> 01:08:59.939
that the partition function
is trace of some matrix raised

01:08:59.939 --> 01:09:03.229
to the N power.

01:09:03.229 --> 01:09:07.410
And if I diagonalize the
matrix, what I will get

01:09:07.410 --> 01:09:12.450
is the sum over all eigenvalues
raised to the N power.

01:09:16.180 --> 01:09:20.880
Now note that we expect
phase transitions to occur,

01:09:20.880 --> 01:09:27.250
not for any finite system,
but only in the limit where

01:09:27.250 --> 01:09:28.899
there are many
degrees of freedom.

01:09:31.450 --> 01:09:34.600
And, actually, if
I have such a sum

01:09:34.600 --> 01:09:38.280
as this in the limit of
very large number of degrees

01:09:38.280 --> 01:09:46.270
of freedom, this becomes
lambda max to the power of N.

01:09:46.270 --> 01:09:50.310
Now in order to get any one of
these series of eigenvalues,

01:09:50.310 --> 01:09:52.109
what should I do?

01:09:52.109 --> 01:09:56.370
I should take a matrix,
which is this e to the T--

01:09:56.370 --> 01:09:59.110
e to the strength
of the interactions.

01:09:59.110 --> 01:10:04.040
What did I write? e to
the K of S and S prime.

01:10:04.040 --> 01:10:07.020
So there is a matrix.

01:10:07.020 --> 01:10:10.392
All of its elements
are Boltzmann weights.

01:10:10.392 --> 01:10:11.350
There are all positive.

01:10:17.860 --> 01:10:21.370
And find the eigenvalues
of this matrix.

01:10:21.370 --> 01:10:29.030
Now for the case of the Ising
model without a magnetic field,

01:10:29.030 --> 01:10:30.470
the matrix is 2 x 2.

01:10:30.470 --> 01:10:34.290
It's e to the K, corresponding
to the diagonal terms

01:10:34.290 --> 01:10:37.620
where the spins are
parallel, e to the minus K

01:10:37.620 --> 01:10:41.140
when the spins are antiparallel.

01:10:41.140 --> 01:10:45.350
And clearly you can see that the
eigenvalues corresponding to 1,

01:10:45.350 --> 01:10:53.050
1 or 1, minus 1 as eigenvectors,
are hyperbolic cosine of K--

01:10:53.050 --> 01:10:54.940
strike this.

01:10:54.940 --> 01:10:59.765
e to the K plus e to the
minus K e to the K minus

01:10:59.765 --> 01:11:06.450
e to the minus K. You
can see that to get this,

01:11:06.450 --> 01:11:10.490
all I had to do was to
diagonalize a matrix that

01:11:10.490 --> 01:11:16.000
corresponded to one
bond, if you like.

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:19.650
And just as in here,
there is no reason

01:11:19.650 --> 01:11:23.010
to expect that these
eigenvalues, which

01:11:23.010 --> 01:11:25.420
depend on this
set of parameters,

01:11:25.420 --> 01:11:29.550
should non-analytical functions.

01:11:29.550 --> 01:11:32.070
There is no reason
for non-analyticity

01:11:32.070 --> 01:11:34.705
as long as you are dealing
with a single bond.

01:11:34.705 --> 01:11:40.190
We expect non-analyticities
at their limit of large N.

01:11:40.190 --> 01:11:46.810
So if each one of these
is analytic function of K,

01:11:46.810 --> 01:11:50.505
the only way spanning the K
axis that I could encounter

01:11:50.505 --> 01:11:55.860
in non-analyticity is if two
of these eigenvalues cross,

01:11:55.860 --> 01:11:59.730
because we have seen a
potential mechanism for phase

01:11:59.730 --> 01:12:00.470
transitions.

01:12:00.470 --> 01:12:02.816
We discussed this in A333.

01:12:02.816 --> 01:12:05.310
That if we have sum
of contributions,

01:12:05.310 --> 01:12:08.302
that each one of them is
exponentially large in N,

01:12:08.302 --> 01:12:10.820
and two of these
contributions cross,

01:12:10.820 --> 01:12:14.020
then your partition function
will jump from one hill

01:12:14.020 --> 01:12:14.870
to another hill.

01:12:14.870 --> 01:12:16.970
And you will have a
discontinuity, let's say,

01:12:16.970 --> 01:12:19.260
in derivatives or whatever.

01:12:19.260 --> 01:12:22.690
So the potential
mechanism that I can have

01:12:22.690 --> 01:12:26.040
is that if I have as
a function of changing

01:12:26.040 --> 01:12:29.460
one of my parameters or a
bunch of these parameters,

01:12:29.460 --> 01:12:31.760
the ordering of
these eigenvalues--

01:12:31.760 --> 01:12:34.610
let's say lambda 0 is
the largest one, lambda

01:12:34.610 --> 01:12:37.070
1 is the next one,
lambda 2, et cetera.

01:12:37.070 --> 01:12:41.180
So each one of them
is going its own way.

01:12:41.180 --> 01:12:47.500
If the largest one suddenly
gets crossed by something else,

01:12:47.500 --> 01:12:52.010
then you willl basically abandon
one eigenvalue for another,

01:12:52.010 --> 01:12:55.490
and you will have a mechanism
for a phase transition.

01:12:55.490 --> 01:12:59.680
So what I told you was that
there is a theorem that

01:12:59.680 --> 01:13:03.320
for a matrix where all of
the eigenvalues are positive,

01:13:03.320 --> 01:13:05.650
this will never happen.

01:13:05.650 --> 01:13:11.450
The largest eigenvalue
will remain non-degenerate.

01:13:11.450 --> 01:13:13.720
And there is some
analog of this,

01:13:13.720 --> 01:13:16.830
probably you've seen
in quantum mechanics,

01:13:16.830 --> 01:13:19.090
that if you have a
potential, the ground

01:13:19.090 --> 01:13:20.640
state is non-degenerate.

01:13:20.640 --> 01:13:23.200
The ground state is
always a function

01:13:23.200 --> 01:13:26.390
that is positive everywhere.

01:13:26.390 --> 01:13:28.210
And the next
excitation would have

01:13:28.210 --> 01:13:30.860
to have a node go
from plus to minus.

01:13:30.860 --> 01:13:34.490
And somehow you cannot
have the eigenvalues cross.

01:13:34.490 --> 01:13:39.060
So in a similar sense, it turns
out the largest eigenvalue,

01:13:39.060 --> 01:13:41.830
the largest eigenvector
for these matrices,

01:13:41.830 --> 01:13:44.590
will have all of the
elements positive,

01:13:44.590 --> 01:13:46.800
and it cannot become degenerate.

01:13:46.800 --> 01:13:51.390
And so you are guaranteed
that this will not happen.

01:13:51.390 --> 01:13:53.890
Now the second part of
this story that I briefly

01:13:53.890 --> 01:13:58.530
mentioned was you can repeat
this for two dimensions,

01:13:58.530 --> 01:14:01.860
for three dimensions,
higher dimensional things.

01:14:01.860 --> 01:14:04.640
So one thing that
you could do is,

01:14:04.640 --> 01:14:08.310
rather than sorting the
Ising model on a line,

01:14:08.310 --> 01:14:13.010
you can solve it on a ladder,
or a ladder that has two rungs.

01:14:13.010 --> 01:14:17.910
So solving the Ising
model on this structure

01:14:17.910 --> 01:14:19.840
is not very
difficult because you

01:14:19.840 --> 01:14:25.330
can say that there are eight
possible values that this

01:14:25.330 --> 01:14:26.910
can take.

01:14:26.910 --> 01:14:29.095
And so I can construct
a matrix that

01:14:29.095 --> 01:14:33.810
is 8 x 8 that tells me how I
go from the choice of eight

01:14:33.810 --> 01:14:38.370
possibilities here to the
eight possibilities there.

01:14:38.370 --> 01:14:41.820
And I will have an 8 x 8 matrix
that has these properties

01:14:41.820 --> 01:14:44.570
and will satisfy this.

01:14:44.570 --> 01:14:50.090
It will be true if
I go to a 4 strip.

01:14:50.090 --> 01:14:52.330
It will be a 16 x 16.

01:14:52.330 --> 01:14:53.230
No problem.

01:14:53.230 --> 01:14:55.180
I can keep going.

01:14:55.180 --> 01:14:58.520
And it would say, well,
the two-dimensional--

01:14:58.520 --> 01:15:01.160
and also you could do
three-dimensional or higher

01:15:01.160 --> 01:15:05.226
dimensional models-- should
not have a phase transition.

01:15:05.226 --> 01:15:08.180
Well, it turns out
that all of this

01:15:08.180 --> 01:15:11.930
relies on having
a finite matrix.

01:15:11.930 --> 01:15:17.220
And what Onsager showed
was that, indeed,

01:15:17.220 --> 01:15:20.180
for any finite strip, you
would have a situation

01:15:20.180 --> 01:15:22.375
such as this-- actually
more accurately

01:15:22.375 --> 01:15:28.720
if I were to draw a
situation such as this, where

01:15:28.720 --> 01:15:32.860
two eigenvalues would
approach but will never cross.

01:15:32.860 --> 01:15:35.470
And one can show that
the gap between them

01:15:35.470 --> 01:15:40.930
will scale as something
like 1 over this length.

01:15:40.930 --> 01:15:45.680
And so in the limit where you
go to a large enough system,

01:15:45.680 --> 01:15:48.875
you have the
possibility of ascension

01:15:48.875 --> 01:15:54.390
to some singularity when two
eigenvalues touch each other.

01:15:54.390 --> 01:15:57.780
So this scenario is very
well known and studied

01:15:57.780 --> 01:15:58.830
in two dimensions.

01:15:58.830 --> 01:16:00.270
In higher dimensions,
we actually

01:16:00.270 --> 01:16:04.550
don't really know what happens.

01:16:04.550 --> 01:16:05.050
OK.

01:16:05.050 --> 01:16:06.687
Any questions?

