01:16:36.890 --> 01:16:43.260
If I have an L x N system
in which you keep L finite

01:16:43.260 --> 01:16:47.650
and set N going to infinity,
you won't see a singularity.

01:16:47.650 --> 01:16:53.130
But if I have an N x N system,
and I said N goes to infinity,

01:16:53.130 --> 01:16:56.240
I will encounter a
singularity in the limit

01:16:56.240 --> 01:16:57.616
of N going to infinity.

01:17:01.360 --> 01:17:03.370
Again, very roughly,
one can also

01:17:03.370 --> 01:17:07.610
should develop a physical
picture of what's going on.

01:17:07.610 --> 01:17:13.940
So let's imagine that
you have a system that

01:17:13.940 --> 01:17:20.040
is a very large number but
finite in one direction.

01:17:20.040 --> 01:17:26.070
And this other direction can
be two, can be three, whatever.

01:17:26.070 --> 01:17:28.960
You have a finite size.

01:17:28.960 --> 01:17:33.620
But in this other
direction, you basically

01:17:33.620 --> 01:17:37.150
can go as large as you like.

01:17:37.150 --> 01:17:42.640
Now presumably this
two-dimensional model

01:17:42.640 --> 01:17:46.750
has a phase transition if
it was infinite x infinite.

01:17:46.750 --> 01:17:49.150
And on approaching
that phase transition,

01:17:49.150 --> 01:17:50.950
there would be a
correlation length

01:17:50.950 --> 01:17:54.460
that would diverge
with this exponent nu.

01:17:54.460 --> 01:17:57.280
So let's say I am sufficiently
far away from the phase

01:17:57.280 --> 01:18:01.680
transition that the correlation
length is something like this.

01:18:01.680 --> 01:18:05.270
So this patch of spins
knows about each other.

01:18:05.270 --> 01:18:07.580
If I go closer to
the transition,

01:18:07.580 --> 01:18:09.395
it will grow bigger and bigger.

01:18:09.395 --> 01:18:12.840
At some point, it will fit
the size of the system,

01:18:12.840 --> 01:18:15.950
and then it cannot
grow any further.

01:18:15.950 --> 01:18:18.520
So beyond that,
what you will see

01:18:18.520 --> 01:18:20.420
is essentially
there is one patch

01:18:20.420 --> 01:18:23.780
here, one patch
here, one patch here.

01:18:23.780 --> 01:18:27.000
And you are back to a
one-dimensional system.

01:18:27.000 --> 01:18:29.630
So what happens is that
your correlation length

01:18:29.630 --> 01:18:33.560
starts to grow as if you were
in two dimensions or three

01:18:33.560 --> 01:18:34.650
dimensions.

01:18:34.650 --> 01:18:37.480
Once it hits the
size of the system,

01:18:37.480 --> 01:18:38.760
then it has to saturate.

01:18:38.760 --> 01:18:40.610
It cannot grow any bigger.

01:18:40.610 --> 01:18:45.930
And then this block becomes
independent of the next block.

01:18:45.930 --> 01:18:50.080
So essentially, you would say
that you would have effectively

01:18:50.080 --> 01:18:54.260
a one-dimensional system where
the number of blocks that you

01:18:54.260 --> 01:19:06.980
have is of the
order of N over L.

